      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can achieve the same functionality in Rust with the following code:\n\n```rust\nuse std::vec::Vec;\n\nstruct DataBuffer {\n    buffer: Vec<i32>,\n}\n\nimpl DataBuffer {\n    fn new(size: usize) -> Self {\n        DataBuffer {\n            buffer: Vec::with_capacity(size),\n        }\n    }\n\n    fn set_val(&mut self, idx: usize, val: i32) {\n        if idx < self.buffer.len() {\n            self.buffer[idx] = val;\n        }\n    }\n\n    fn get_val(&self, idx: usize) -> i32 {\n        self.buffer.get(idx).cloned().unwrap_or(-1)\n    }\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    let mut db = DataBuffer::new(10);\n    db.set_val(5, 42);\n    println!(\"Value at 5: {}\", db.get_val(5));\n}\n```\n\nThis Rust code creates a `DataBuffer` struct with a vector of `i32` values. The `set_val` and `get_val` methods are implemented to match the behavior of the original C++ code. Note that Rust's `Vec` is a growable vector, so you don't need to specify the size when creating it",
